e Antique Rome, ad 300–500 -- t14. Religious Minorities in Late Roman Italy: Jewish City-Dwellers and Their Non-Jewish Neighbours -- tPart V: Culture -- t15. Christian Sarcophagi in Late Roman Italy: Culture and Connection -- t16. Late Roman Italy in Latin Panegyric: From the Panegyrici Latini to Ennodius -- t17. Stepping Out of the Shadows: Italy in Late Antique Historiography -- tEpilogue: Late Roman Italy – Paths Explored and Paths to Explore -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the major political, social, economic, religious and cultural changes impacting what was once the most important region of the Roman worldThe first modern research volume on a core region of Late AntiquityA tight and distinctly chronological focus on the second quarter of the first millennium CE, that allows for a different vision of the many vicissitudes of Late Roman Italy, among other works on Ancient and Late Antique Italy.An emphasis on one of the key features of Late Antiquity: the transformation of the Roman Empire in the West into successor polities.A balanced range of topics, including ones rarely encountered in this type of work (such as gender or environmental history), with a special focus on political transformation and violence.This research volume reassesses one of the most fundamental transformations in Late Antiquity, centered on a pivotal region: the transition from ‘Empire’ to ‘Kingdom’ in Italy c. 250-500. During the first quarter of the first millennium, Italy was still the heart of the Roman Empire; the only political superstructure ever managing to encompass the entire Mediterranean world and its European hinterland. Yet during the second quarter of this millennium, Italy underwent dramatic evolutions from demotion to a provincialized region (c. 285-395), to a new imperial hub kept afloat by cannibalizing other provinces’ resources (c. 395-476), to an autonomous regnum governed by non-Roman rulers as part of an Eastern Roman ‘Commonwealth’ (c. 475-535).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aArends, Niels P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, Miriam A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphries, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenski, Noel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonard, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCunn, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeil, Bronwen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNuffelen, Peter Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmissi, Adrastos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRance, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberto, Umberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchoolman, Edward M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlootjes, Daniëlle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTraina, Giusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVihervalli, Ulriika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWesteinde, Jessica van ’t, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWijnendaele, Jeroen W. P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWijnendaele, Jeroen,